With Janel McCarville scoring 19 points, grabbing nine rebounds and passing the ball as well as any point guard, host Minnesota rolled to an 86-34 win over Detroit Mercy on 
Thursday.
article.headline: McCarville's 18 points, 9 boards lead dominant show
article.linkText: Minnesota shows no mercy toward Detroit
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- No. 18 Minnesota has struggled with sloppy
play that has kept their games closer than desired.

Not this time.

With Janel McCarville scoring 19 points, grabbing nine rebounds
and passing the ball as well as any point guard, the Gophers rolled
to an 86-34 win over Detroit Mercy.

It marked the fewest points allowed and the largest margin of
victory by a Minnesota team since the school entered the NCAA in
1981-82.

"We put a very good 40-minute game together," said Minnesota
coach Pam Borton. "We could easily have come out at halftime like
we did the last two games and got back on our heels a little bit
and let the other team back in. We did not do that tonight."

The Gophers averaged 20 turnovers in their first four games of
the season. Against Detroit, they gave up the ball only 12 times.

"That's been our Achilles heel," said Borton. "That's
something we've really been working on, slowing it down, working
for the better shot, playing more team basketball."

After taking a 52-22 lead at the break, the Gophers (5-1)
outscored the Titans 22-2 for a 76-24 lead.

McCarville, who was shooting just 36 percent coming into the
game, was 6-for-11 in her fourth appearance since recovering from a
broken right hand suffered in preseason practice.

"I think I have (got) a long way to go, but I'm making steps to
get there," said McCarville, who added three assists. "I don't
think I'm quite there yet. And it's a good thing, it's only
December."

Kelly Roysland tied a career-high with 16 points in her second
start of the season, and Jamie Broback had 14 for the Gophers, who
won their 22nd straight non-conference home game.

Lindsey Pasquinzo had 10 points to lead Detroit, which made just
15-of-55 shots. No one else scored in double figures.

" ... we blew it," said Detroit coach Mickey Barrett. "We
picked a bad time to have a bad day."

The Gophers shot 55 percent from the floor, and out-rebounded
the Titans 49-22.

Minnesota took control early, using a 20-4 spurt for a 30-11
lead. The run was highlighted by Liz Podominick's fast-break basket
off an over-the-head pass by Shannon Schonrock. A backdoor bounce
pass from McCarville to Roysland led to a baseline layup.

The game turned into a laugher when McCarville grabbed a loose
ball while teetering on the baseline, then handed it to Detroit's
Katie Solner, who was standing out of bounds. McCarville punctuated
the Harlem Globetrotter-type play with a basket and free throw for
a 41-20 Gopher lead.

The Titans (1-3) never got closer.

Back-to-back 3-pointers by Schonrock improved Minnesota's lead
to 64-24. Leslie Knight's free throws with 6:10 left made it 82-28.

The previous low allowed by a Minnesota team was a 72-40 win
over Northwestern on Jan. 8, 2004. The previous largest margin of
victory was a 114-65 win over Butler on Nov. 17, 2001.
